  "text": "In this metaphor, \"speakers are analogous to producers and sellers, [and] listeners and viewers are analogous to buyers and consumers\" (Riley 2005, 164) Brennan thus explained that freedom of speech has little power if others cannot receive, or access, that speech. A marketplace without buyers, he speculates, would soon become a marketplace without sellers, thus eliminating the purpose of and need for a market. The ability to \"buy\"-to access information-is necessary to constitute a market. As Phillip M. [CITATION_1] noted, \"By the mid-1960s, the marketplace metaphor had fully crystallized into a concise expression of a key dimension of the First Amendment\" (155).",
  "correct_citation": {
